        <h2>What is Kareo?</h2>
        <p>
          Kareo is a SaaS platform for small medical offices. It offers products for writing clinical notes called an EHR (Electronic Health Record System),
          managing medical billing, scheduling, and communicating &amp; engaging with patients (Patient Portal). Typical customers include small family medicine physicians and
          physical therapists.
        </p>
        <p>
          Large hospital systems typically don't use Kareo because they have infrastructure
          and resources to handle billing themselves. Smaller practices aren't so business savvy and so they look to
          outsourced billing solutions which can be costly. An easy-to-use billing system that connects elegantly with
          an EHR is a very valuable proposition. Kareo aims to do this.
        </p>
        <h2>Patient Portal</h2>
        <figure>
          <%= image_tag "portal.jpg" %>
        </figure>
        <h3>Why make a patient portal?</h3>
        <p>
          Patient Portals are web products that are typically bundled with EHRs.
          They allow patients to access their health record and communicate with their providers.
          With the Patient Portal, we saw and opportunity to increase patient engagement
          and revenue volume for our customers.
        </p>
        <p>
          One of our goals was to increase patient health awareness by making health information
          easy to get to and easy to understand.For practices, our goal was to increase patient
          responsiblity payments. In 2010, the US healthcare industry wrote off <a href="https://www.jpmorgan.com/cm/BlobServer/JPM-KeyTrends-in-HealthcarePatientPayments.pdf?blobkey=id&blobwhere=1320610345938&blobheader=application/pdf&blobheadername1=Cache-Control&blobheadervalue1=private&blobcol=urldata&blobtable=MungoBlobs" target="_blank">$65 billion</a>
          in bad debt accrued from not collecting patient payments. For our customers, the
          problem lies in archaic payment practices, which we hoped to innovate with Patient Portal.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <%= image_tag "early-portal-notes.jpg" %>
        </figure>
        <h3>User Research</h3>
        <p>
          We learned from interviews with patients and healthcare professionals that:
        </p>

        <blockquote>
          Patients don't care about statement details; they just want to know what they owe and how to pay it.
        </blockquote>

        <p>
          This was difficult for us to believe. How could patients not care about what they're paying for? We
          listened to the feedback and designed a payment solution that payment solution (using Stripe) that
          connected to the Patient Portal. But we also let patients make payments without logging in,
          authenticating, and viewing their statements. All they could see if what they owed and to whom.
        </p>
        <h3>Structure</h3>
        <p>
          Patient Portal's structure is quite complex. Certain functionality won't work if the customer
          doesn't have certain products enabled. For example, patient's can't make payments if the practice
          doesn't have Kareo Practice Management. We want to change this (we're currently working on this now)
          so practices can collect the money and work with an in-house biller or outsourced biller to
          adjudicate the amount. The value in signing up for the full Kareo suite is a lot of that work
          is done automatically. Above you can see the basic structure of how patients can interact with
          their practices with three typical scenarios.
        </p>
